<para id="element-212">If <emphasis effect="italics">A</emphasis> and <emphasis effect="italics">B</emphasis> are <term>mutually exclusive</term>, then <emphasis effect="italics">P</emphasis>(<emphasis effect="italics">A</emphasis> AND <emphasis effect="italics">B</emphasis>) = 0. Then <emphasis effect="italics">P</emphasis>(<emphasis effect="italics">A</emphasis> OR <emphasis effect="italics">B</emphasis>) = <emphasis effect="italics">P</emphasis>(<emphasis effect="italics">A</emphasis>) + <emphasis effect="italics">P</emphasis>(<emphasis effect="italics">B</emphasis>) − <emphasis effect="italics">P</emphasis>(<emphasis effect="italics">A</emphasis> AND <emphasis effect="italics">B</emphasis>) becomes <newline/><emphasis effect="italics">P</emphasis>(<emphasis effect="italics">A</emphasis> OR <emphasis effect="italics">B</emphasis>) = <emphasis effect="italics">P</emphasis>(<emphasis effect="italics">A</emphasis>) + <emphasis effect="italics">P</emphasis>(<emphasis effect="italics">B</emphasis>).</para>
<para id="fs-id1164567307413">Draw one card from a standard deck of playing cards. Let <emphasis effect="italics">H</emphasis> = the card is a heart and <emphasis effect="italics">S</emphasis> = the card is a spade. These events are mutually exclusive because a card cannot be a heart and a spade at the same time. The probability that the card is a heart or a spade is</para>
